marked: Sensory deficits in PD patients are evident both in somatosensory pathways, e.g. coding for proprioception and kinaesthesia

In summary, characterizing the effect of STN-DBS on the sensory processing of urinary bladder afferents may extend our understanding (i) how STN-DBS affects the processing of sensory information in PD, (ii) how the basal ganglia interact with sensory systems and (iii) how changes in sensory gating processes modify behavioural strategies.
